$ /etc/apt/sources.list

The file contains the locations of → Linux/package-managers/APT#apt-repositories[apt repositories] to fetch packages from.

Such repositories are added or removed with `→ Linux/APT/commands/add-apt-repository`.

The content of `sources.list` looks like
code {
deb http://deb.debian.org/debian bullseye main
deb http://deb.debian.org/debian bullseye-updates main
deb http://security.debian.org/debian-security bullseye-security main
deb http://ftp.debian.org/debian bullseye-backports main
code }
  
sa:

  The `/etc/apt/sources.list.d` and `→ Linux/fhs/etc/apt` directories.

 `→ Linux/package-managers/APT/commands/apt upgrade`

 `→ Linux/package-managers/APT/commands/apt edit-sources` edits `/etc/apt/sources.list` in the preferred → development/editors[editor].

 `→ Linux/shell/commands/man 5 sources.list`

 `→ Linux/fhs/var/lib/apt/lists` is the *storage area for state information for each package resource specified in `sources.list`*

code {
→ Linux/package-managers/APT/commands/apt-config dump | grep Dir::Etc::source
code }

  `sources.list` specifies the locations which are used to resynchronize the *package index files* with `→ Linux/package-managers/APT/commands/apt-get update`.

  `add-apt-repository` is a Python script with which an APT repository can be added to or removed from `/etc/apt/sources.list` or a file under the `/etc/apt/sources.list.d` directory.
   -
   This script can be added with `sudo apt install -y software-properties-common`
  
